Patient received COVID 19 vaccine the morning of 1/18/21 at Public Health COVID-19 vaccine clinic. I (person completing this report) work for PH. Later that night while in bed, patient reported difficulty breathing to his wife, then turned blue, and became unresponsive. Family report pt was without any symptoms prior to event.  911 called; CPR started by family member 15 min. after pt became unresponsive. EMS performed resuscitation for about 30-40 minutes with multiple defibrillation for V-fib.  Between EMS and Medical Center ER, pt had 9 rounds of epi, CPR w/ LUCAS  machine, given 2 doses of amiodarone (150 mg and 300 mg). Patient had 3 EKGs, which did not show STEMI, but did show nonspecific conduction delay and sinus arrest with junctional escape vs sinus bradycardia (HR 50's).  Pt had return of spontaneous circulation. Pt intubated, and started on Levophed. Pt transferred to ICU, and had central line placed.  Family decided to make patient DNR. Pt went into coarse VFib again, and as per wishes of family, code blue not called.  Patient expired at 01:53 on 1/19/21.
LAB_DATA: Patient had 3 EKGs, which did not show STEMI, but did show nonspecific conduction delay and sinus arrest with junctional escape vs sinus bradycardia (HR 50's). Laboratory work done indicated that cardiac enzymes were normal, and that the patient had metabolic acidosis. Cardiology was called, but no need for emergent cath noted.  Pt. has POCUS echocardiogram, which showed severe cardiomyopathy with LVEF 20%, and no pericardial effusion.  Portable CXR read as: Extensive opacity in R upper lobe and diffuse opacities throughout the L hemithorax are nonspecific, but suggestive of multifocal pneumonia, including COVID-19.  CTA Chest for PE w/ Contrast: Impression: no evidence of pulmonary embolism; bilateral extensive airspace consolidation, cannot exclude pneumonia, aspiration; follow-up barium series recommended to foreign body/filling defect in esophagus (Mediastinum findings: There is thickening involving esophagus and a small hiatal hernia.  Gastric bypass surgery.  There is dense artifact from the mid lumen of the esophagus measuring 8mm).
OTHER_MEDS: per hospital list: Nitrostat 0.4 mg SL prn, famotidine 10 mg,  ASA 81 mg, atorvastatin 20 mg, benazepril 5 mg, carvedilol dose unspecified
CUR_ILL: unknown; family report pt without symptoms prior to event

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Monday, January 25, 2021, at 11:40am I received the second dose of a series for the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine. Over the course of the rest of that day, I began to develop a headache and mild neck soreness. That night, I slept poorly. When I awoke just before 5:00am the next day, Tuesday, January 26, I did not feel well. I was experiencing headache, malaise, nausea, myalgia, arthralgia, and low-grade fever. I called my supervisor around 5:30am that day and we decided it was best that I stay home to recuperate. Throughout the day, I mostly rested and slept, took Tylenol, and began to feel better in the mid-afternoon. I did call and leave a voicemail for hospital Employee Health around 1:30pm on Tuesday the 26th, but did not hear back. Today, Wednesday, January 27, I am feeling much better, and well enough to come to work.

The vaccine was administered on the following date: 1/19/21 and at approximately the following time: 10:30 AM   She works at medical and received vaccine there.    She waited the 15 mins and felt fine. Left work at 1 pm. Had blood taken at health clinic for her annual clinic, no meds or testing just a routine blood draw.    She was actually working out when the symptoms developed while she was boxing at her gym. She didn't really realize what was happening, felt a little bit confused. At 4:30 pm she developed difficulty breathing and wheezing, eye swelling (swollen shut), lips with burning and tingling and swelling, hands were swelling with shortness of breath and throat tightness. She noted a rash on the arm that was flat and red (looked like a pattern on her arms). This rash was not raised. She vomited 2 times at the gym. Her boyfriend picked her up and took her to the ED.      ED Note:  "According to the patient, she was otherwise in her normal state of health and received the moderns COVID-19 vaccine earlier this morning at approximately 1030.  Reports feeling largely well over the course the afternoon, ate a salad for lunch but nothing out of the ordinary for her.  Patient states that she was going to the gym at approximately 4 PM she began to develop diffuse itching and rash.  Over the minutes that followed she also began develop some perioral edema and swelling around her eyes.  Also states that her chest felt somewhat tight and had a dry cough.  Due to concern for allergic action, called an car service was brought immediately to the emergency department for further work-up and evaluation." Initial vitals: HR 153 BP 99/56 RR 24 SpO2 96%. Exam with diffuse erythematous rash on trunk, neck and upper extremities. Peri-occular and peri-oral edema. No tongue swelling. No wheeze.    Treated with epi, IV benadryl and oxygen. She was observed for 6 hours and all symptoms resolved, except for some eye puffiness. The eye puffiness lasted for 2 days. Discharged home. No tryptase level sent.    She had never had a severe allergic reaction in the past.

Approximately 20 minutes after vaccine injection, patient complained of tingling in tongue. Patient then noticed a strange taste in her mouth and tongue began feeling "thick" at that time. Approximately 10 minutes later, patient noticed that lips and mouth began feeling numb and tingly.  Our regional MD was called and advised nurses to have epinephrine on standby and to notify EMS. Ambulance arrived approximately 15 minutes after patient alerted staff of reaction. No medications were administered by Health Department staff, however patient did take one Benadryl that she had in her pocket. Upon arrival, EMS advised patient to take second Benadryl pill that she had in her pocket. EMS transported patient to local hospital. Called to check on patient 4 hours later, patient has made a full recovery and is resting at home. Patient states that she was given a steroid at the hospital and monitored for several hours before being sent home.
LAB_DATA: Blood Pressure taken as soon as patient notified medical staff of adverse reaction, initial reading was 118/80. Blood pressure taken 15 minutes later, reading was 122/84. Patient transported to hospital by EMS after second reading.

There are two events I am reporting, one each from the first dose on 12/19/20, and the second dose on 1/9/21: Approximately 53 hours after Dose #1: Redness on hands and wrist, rash-like small dot appearance on hands and wrists, skin dryness and tightness  of hands. I experienced no itching of hands or wrists. Approximately 53 hours after Dose #2: Small, painful red pustule-like occurrence on base of right thumb, with the appearance of a few small dots in it. I experienced no itching of  thumb or hand. These events both occurred within the same timeframe following the vaccine doses. Following the first event I was seen in the ER. I checked out fine and they could not say exactly what this was. They said it did not appear to be an allergic reaction to the vaccine because it was not systemic and I had no other symptoms such as trouble breathing. They thought perhaps it was coincidental...I work in the hospital as a radiologic technologist where I hand-wash and hand-sanitize all day. Perhaps I just over-washed that day? However I've worked there for 17 years and never had this happen. The redness and rash dissipated by end of day. Following the second  event I did not follow up with any medical provider. This pustule I got happened while I was at home, and otherwise I felt fine so I left it at that. It took several days for the pustule to  go away. I hope you don't mind but I am writing to report this information in the event it may be helpful to you and I am also reporting it because I want to know if what I experienced could be considered an immune response to the vaccine? Another words, not an allergic response but an immune response ? I can find absolutely nothing about this on-line and no one knows what to make of it. Thank you.
